\begin_layout Title

\series bold
\size larger
Assignment 4
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series default
\size large
Econ 200
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
NOTES: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each sub question is self-contained, which means, for example, assumptions
 from part (b) does not carry to part (c).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A few of these questions are directly taken (or modified slightly) from
 Varian's and Lima's books, as well as Sarah Komisarow's and Grace Tsiang's
 problem sets from previous school year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are a total of 54 points possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Demand; Slustky Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose a consumer has preferences between two goods that are perfect substitute
s.
 Can you change prices in such a way that the entire demand response is
 due to the income effect? (2 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose the price of good x decreases, holding all else constant, can the
 substitute effect be negative.
 Hint: perfect subsitutes.
 (2 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
True, False, or Uncertain? Explain whether you agree or disagree with the
 following statements.
 Be brief (5 lines or less) and be very clear.
 (8 points)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If a good is a normal good, the demand function must have a negative slope.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the demand function has a negative slope, then the good is a normal good.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If a good is inferior, then the demand function must have a positive slope.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the demand function has a positive slope, then the good is inferior.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If a good is a normal good, then the consumer spends an increasing fraction
 of total income on it as income increases.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If two goods are perfect complements, the substitution effect is zero.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If two goods are perfect substitutes, then the substitution effect is zero.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If two goods are perfect complements, then the income effect is positive.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that Alex likes chocolate ice cream and Oreo cookies.
 Suppose that after collecting data some researchers conclude that Alex's
 utility function is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
U(C,I) & = & C^{0.7}I^{0.3}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 denotes consumption of cookies and 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 denotes consumption of ice-cream.
 (7 points)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If Alex's income is 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, the price of ice cream is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{I}$
\end_inset

 and the price of cookies is 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{C}$
\end_inset

, what are the demand functions for ice-cream and cookies? (2 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw the demand functions for ice cream, when (1) 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{C}=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=10$
\end_inset

; (2) 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{C}=4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=10$
\end_inset

; (3) 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{C}=3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m=12$
\end_inset

.
 (3 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Comment on the effect that changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{C}$
\end_inset

 have on demand for ice cream when we hold 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 fixed.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Comment on the effect that changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 have on demand for ice cream when we hold 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{C}$
\end_inset

 fixed.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider a consumer that orders his preferences according to the following
 utility function defined over packs of cigarettes and bottles of beer:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
U(b,c) & = & bc
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The price of a beer bottle equals 2 dollars per bottle and the price of
 cigarettes equals 10 dollars per pack.
 Suppose the consumer's income equals 100 dollars.
 (5 points)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Write down the consumer's optimal consumption problem.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
How many packs of cigarettes does the consumer buy? How many bottles of
 beer? (3 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Plot your solution, draw the budget line, and label the optimal bundle with
 the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Continue with problem 5, suppose now that the price of beer decreases to
 1 dollar per bottle.
 (16 points)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that the consumer is compensated for the decrease in the price of
 beer with sufficient money so that he can still barely afford the consumption
 bundle he purchased before the price of beer bottles decreased.
 What would his new income level be? (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
How many beer bottles and cigarette packs does the consumer purchase at
 the lower price of beer and his new income? (3 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw a dotted line that represents the new budget line and label the new
 optimal point, Points 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{S}$
\end_inset

.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Does the substitution effect of the decrease in the price of beer lead the
 consumer to purchase more or fewer beer bottles? How about packs of cigarettes?
 How many more or less of each? (2 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
How many beer bottles and packs of cigarettes does the consumer purchase
 at the new prices and his original income? (3 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw this new budget line in and label the new optimal consumption bundle,
 point 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw lines that are perpendicular to the axis with beer on it that pass
 through points 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{S}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Label the income effect, the substitution effect, and the total effect
 of the price change on demand for beer bottles.
 What is the magnitude of the substitution effect? What is the magnitude
 of the income effect? (4 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Explain the economic importance of decomposing a price change into an income
 and a substitution effect.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Part
Welfare and elasticities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the inverse demand function: 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(\frac{x}{\alpha})^{\frac{1}{\beta}}$
\end_inset

.
 Calculate the own-price elasticity of demand.
 Express your answer as a function of the parameters only.
 How does your answer depend on the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

? (4 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the demand function: (7 points)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
x & = & 400-\frac{1}{2}p
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the own-price elasticity of demand when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=100$
\end_inset

.
 (2 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the own-price elasticity of demand when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=390$
\end_inset

.
 (2 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compare the two numbers you found in parts a and b.
 Interpret the magnitudes that you found.
 (1 point)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
At what point is 
\begin_inset Formula $|\epsilon|=1$
\end_inset

? (2 points) 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate the change in consumer surplus for a consumer whose marginal willingne
ss-to-pay is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $p=10-4x$
\end_inset

, when the price of a good decreases from 
\begin_inset Formula $p=4$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 Sketch a graph to illustrate the gain in consumer surplus described above.
 (3 points)
\end_layout

